MRI-Based Detection of Alzheimer’s Disease and Mild Cognitive Impairment
¶

Roni Tibon: Roni.Tibon@city.ac.uk
¶

The code below applies multiple machine learning techniques to the BioFIND and ADNI datasets in order to classify individuals with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) and Alzheimer's disease against healthy controls.

Define Sets¶

X and y are the features and target sets, respectively. The data is split into train (90%) and test sets (10%).

In [4]:
# Define "X" and "y": Train in BioFIND and test on ADNI

X_train = BioFIND_data.iloc[:,0:30]
y_train = BioFIND_data.iloc[:,30]

X_test = ADNI_data.iloc[:,0:30]
y_test = ADNI_data.iloc[:,30]

# Change type

X_train = np.float32(X_train)
X_test = np.float32(X_test)

y_train = np.int64(y_train)
y_test = np.int64(y_test)

# #%%writefile ClassifierMLP.py # uncomment to recreate the ClassifierMLP.py file. This file is also avaliable in the submitted folder.

import torch.nn as nn
import torch.nn.functional as F

# Define the class for the network
class ClassifierMLP(nn.Module):
     def __init__(self, num_units=10, dropout=0.0, nonlin=F.relu): # these will vary based on the grid search
         super(ClassifierMLP, self).__init__()

         self.dropout = nn.Dropout(dropout)    # always set to 0, following preliminary examination
         self.nonlin = nonlin                  # nonlinear activation is either relu or leaky_relu 
         self.hidden = nn.Linear(30, num_units) # num unit is either 3 or 5       
         self.output = nn.Linear(num_units, 2) 

     def forward(self, X, **kwargs):
         X = self.nonlin(self.hidden(X))
         X = self.dropout(X)
         X = F.softmax(self.output(X), dim=-1)
         return X
In [7]:
net = NeuralNetClassifier(
     ClassifierMLP,
     verbose = 0,
     max_epochs = 5,               # kept low to avoid overfitting
     callbacks = [EarlyStopping()], # apply early stopping
     iterator_train__shuffle=True,
     optimizer = torch.optim.SGD,   # SGD optimiser. Adam was also tested in preliminary examination
     optimizer__momentum=0.7        # avoid local minima
 )

Plot Confusion Matrix¶

In [133]:
def plot_conf(y_train, y_pred_train, y_test, y_pred_test, algo, cmap):
    
    confm_train = pd.crosstab(y_train, y_pred_train, margins = False, normalize='all')
    confm_test = pd.crosstab(y_test, y_pred_test, margins = False, normalize='all')    
    
    f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5), sharey=True)
    #f.suptitle(algo, fontsize=18)

    sns.heatmap(ax=axes[0], data=confm_train, cmap=cmap, annot=True, annot_kws={"fontsize":24}, vmin=0, vmax=1)
    axes[0].set_title('Train Set', fontsize=30)
    axes[0].set_xlabel("Predicted Class", fontsize=24); axes[0].set_ylabel("Actual Class", fontsize=24)
    axes[0].set_xticks([0.5,1.5]); axes[0].set_xticklabels(['HC','PN'], fontsize=20)
    axes[0].set_yticks([0.5,1.5]); axes[0].set_yticklabels(['HC','PN'], fontsize=20)
    sns.heatmap(ax=axes[1], data=confm_test, cmap=cmap, annot=True, annot_kws={"fontsize":24}, vmin=0, vmax=1)
    axes[1].set_title('Test Set', fontsize=30)
    axes[1].set_xlabel("Predicted Class", fontsize=24); axes[1].set_ylabel("Actual Class", fontsize=24)
    axes[1].set_xticks([0.5,1.5]); axes[1].set_xticklabels(['HC','PN'], fontsize=20)
    axes[1].set_yticks([0.5,1.5]); axes[1].set_yticklabels(['HC','PN'], fontsize=20)
    
    return None

Plot ROC and AUC¶

In [129]:
def plot_roc(estimator, algo, cmap):
    
    
    dt_disp_train = plot_roc_curve(estimator, X_train, y_train, C=cmap, linewidth=3)
    ax = plt.gca()
    dt_disp_test = plot_roc_curve(estimator, X_test, y_test, ax=ax, alpha=0.8, C=cmap, linestyle='--', linewidth=3)
    ax = plt.gca()
    #ax.title.set_text(algo)
    ax.title.set_text('ROC')
    ax.title.set_size(30)
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=20); ax.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=20)
    ax.set_xlabel("False Positive Rate", fontsize=24); ax.set_ylabel("True Positive Rate", fontsize=24)
    plt.style.use('fast')
        
    return None

Print accuracy, recall and precision¶

In [10]:
def view_matrices(y_train, y_test, y_pred_train, y_pred_test, algo):
    
    print('\n-------------------\nMatrices for', algo, '\n-------------------')
    print('\nTRAINING\n')
    print('overall accuracy: ', "%.2f" % metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print('Ctrl recall: ', "%.2f" % metrics.recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print('Ctrl precision: ', "%.2f" % metrics.precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print('Ctrl F1 score: ', "%.2f" % metrics.f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print('MCI recall: ', "%.2f" % metrics.recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train, pos_label=0))
    print('MCI precision: ', "%.2f" % metrics.precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train, pos_label=0))
    print('MCI F1 score: ', "%.2f" % metrics.f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train, pos_label=0))
    
    print('\nTESTING\n')
    print('overall accuracy: ', "%.2f" % metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print('Ctrl recall: ', "%.2f" % metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print('Ctrl precision: ', "%.2f" % metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print('Ctrl F1 score: ', "%.2f" % metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print('MCI recall: ', "%.2f" % metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test, pos_label=0))
    print('MCI precision: ', "%.2f" % metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test, pos_label=0))
    print('MCI F1 score: ', "%.2f" % metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test, pos_label=0))
    
    return None

Classification Algorithms¶

Eight classification algorithms were used. For each algorithm, grid search was performed across a range of values

Decision Tree¶

Non-parametric supervised method. Decision rules are inferred from the data features

In [27]:
# Define parameters for grid

param_grid = {'criterion':['gini','entropy','log_loss'], #function to measure the quality of a split
              'max_depth':[2,4,8,16,22,None], #maximum depth of the tree
              'min_samples_leaf':[1,5,20,40,80], #minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node
              'max_features':[5,15,None]} #number of features to consider when looking for the best split

# Fit models

dt_g = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeClassifier(), param_grid, refit=True, cv=10, scoring='accuracy', return_train_score=True)
dt_g.fit(X_train,y_train)

# Save model: all models in the grid will be saved

    pickle.dump(model, f)

K-Nearest neighbour¶

Supervised method that used for both classification and regression. Finds the distances between a query and all the examples in the data, selects the specified number examples (K) closest to the query, then votes for the most frequent label

In [16]:
# Define parameters for grid

param_grid = {'n_neighbors':[2,3,5,10,20,40,80], #number of neighbors to use
              'metric':['minkowski','cosine','manhattan'], #metric to use for distance computation. when p=2 (default),'minkowski'=euclidean distance
              'algorithm':['ball_tree', 'kd_tree', 'brute']} #algorithm used to compute the nearest neighbors

# Fit models

knn_g = GridSearchCV(KNeighborsClassifier(), param_grid, refit=True, cv=10, scoring='accuracy', return_train_score=True)
knn_g.fit(X_train,y_train)

print("KNN best model: \n", knn_g.best_estimator_, "\n")

# Save model: all models in the grid will be saved

path = "Models\KNN_models_FDAD.pkl" 
model = knn_g

with open(path, 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(model, f)

KNN best model: 
 KNeighborsClassifier(algorithm='ball_tree', n_neighbors=80)

Linear discriminant analysis¶

Makes predictions by estimating the probability that a new set of inputs belongs to each class. The class that gets the highest probability is the output class and a prediction is made. The model uses Bayes Theorem to estimate the probabilities

In [17]:
# Define parameters for grid

param_grid = {'solver':['svd', 'lsqr', 'eigen'], #solver to compute log-posterior. svd does not compute a covariance matrix so cannot be used with shrinkage
              'shrinkage': ['auto', 0, 0.01, 0.02, 0.05, 0.2, 0.4, 0.8, None]} #regularization used to improve the estimation of covariance matrices in situations where the number of training samples is small compared to the number of features. works only with lsqr and eigen solvers

# Fit models

lda_g = GridSearchCV(LinearDiscriminantAnalysis(), param_grid, refit=True, cv=10, scoring='accuracy', return_train_score=True)
lda_g.fit(X_train,y_train)

print("LDA best model: \n", lda_g.best_estimator_, "\n")

# Save model: all models in the grid will be saved

path = "Models\LDA_models_FDAD.pkl" 
model = lda_g

with open(path, 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(model, f)

LDA best model: 
 LinearDiscriminantAnalysis(shrinkage=0.02, solver='lsqr')

Naïve Bayes¶

Supervised learning algorithms based on applying Bayes theorem with the naive assumption of conditional independence between every pair of features given the value of the class variable.

Random Forest¶

Averaging algorithm based on randomized decision trees. An ensenmble of classifiers is created by introducing randomness in the classifier construction. The prediction of the ensemble is given as the averaged prediction of the individual classifiers. By taking an average of those predictions, some errors can cancel out.

In [24]:

    'max_features':[5,15,None]} #number of features to consider when looking for the best split

SVM¶

Maps data points to a high-dimensional space and then finds the optimal hyperplane that divides the data into two classes

In [15]:

# Feature importance based on mean decrease in impurity

importances = rf_g.best_estimator_.feature_importances_
std = np.std([tree.feature_importances_ for tree in rf_g.best_estimator_.estimators_], axis=0)

feature_names = [BioFIND_data.iloc[:,0:30].columns]

#feature_names = [f"feature {i}" for i in range(30)]

forest_importances = pd.Series(importances, index=feature_names)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
forest_importances.plot.bar(yerr=std, ax=ax)
ax.set_title("Feature importances using MDI")
ax.set_ylabel("Mean decrease in impurity")
fig.tight_layout()

# Feature importance based on feature permutation

from sklearn.inspection import permutation_importance

result = permutation_importance(
    rf_g.best_estimator_, X_test, y_test, n_repeats=10, random_state=42, n_jobs=2
)

forest_importances = pd.Series(result.importances_mean, index=feature_names)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
forest_importances.plot.bar(yerr=result.importances_std, ax=ax)
ax.set_title("Feature importances using permutation on full model")
ax.set_ylabel("Mean accuracy decrease")
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()
